# Agent Memory

Two small files in `docs/agent/`:

- `CONTEXT.md` — current state snapshot (refresh in place)
- `LESSONS.md` — hard-won non-obvious gotchas

These complement `AGENTS.md` (project map) and `.cursor/rules/*.mdc` (standing rules). They are NOT a session journal — `git log` + `src/version.ts` CHANGELOG + commit/migration bodies are the journal.

## Start of chat — MANDATORY

Before any other tool call (except reading these files): read `CONTEXT.md` and `LESSONS.md` in full. Both are small by design.

In your first reply, include ONE concise line acknowledging state. Example:

> Session loaded — `main` at v5.61.0, working tree clean.

Skip the read entirely for purely conversational messages ("hi", "thanks").

## Updates — opt-in only, default is write nothing

After a merge / push / commit: **write nothing.** Lior explicitly said the post-merge ritual was a time sink. Don't even mention you skipped it.

Only update when ONE of these is true:

1. Lior explicitly says "update CONTEXT" / "log this" / "remember this" / similar.
2. Real WIP handoff — uncommitted work, blocked on external action, half-done flow the next chat would re-discover from zero.
3. A genuinely new non-obvious gotcha for `LESSONS.md`. Bar is HIGH: must be specific to this stack/data/codebase. Generic engineering advice ("validate inputs", "audit before shipping") does NOT qualify — that's rule material or nothing.

## Formats

**`CONTEXT.md`** — refresh in place when state materially changed (new version on `main`, new WIP, follow-up resolved):

- Keep under 30 lines total.
- Bullets only, no paragraphs.
- Update "Last refreshed" date.
- If it grows past 30 lines, prune the oldest item.

**`LESSONS.md`** — append a new entry only when a real incident exposed a gotcha future agents would re-hit. Hard cap 5 lines per lesson:

```
## Short title

**Gotcha**: one sentence.
**Fix**: one sentence (or 2-3 short bullets).
**Burned**: when/where it bit us.
```

Cap LESSONS at ~10 entries total. Adding a new one means an older one is either promoted to a `.cursor/rules/*.mdc` rule (if it's now "how we work") or deleted.

## What does NOT belong here

- Bug-fix narratives → commit message body (or nowhere)
- Architecture decisions → SQL/code header comments or `AGENTS.md`
- Standing conventions → `.cursor/rules/*.mdc`
- Release notes → `src/version.ts` CHANGELOG
- Session journals → `git log`

Documentation sprawl is the enemy. If you find yourself writing the same thing in two places, stop and pick one.
